  <div class="topic">
    <h4>Step 2: border-box</h4>
    <p>Uh oh. It looks like the border threw off our sizing:</p>
    <img src="http://www.elevationacademy.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Screen-Shot-2016-03-06-at-2.51.28-PM.png">

    <p>If you remember back to our conversations about the CSS Box Model, you'll remember that the border of an element adds to the elements size. In our example, our div's are now slightly wider than 8.33333333%, making the last column jump to a new row.</p>

    <p>Lucky for us, there's a CSS property to change this behavior: <strong>box-sizing</strong>. Look at the example below that toggles between:</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8">box-sizing: content-box;</pre>

    <p>and</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8">box-sizing: border-box;</pre>

    <iframe id="cp_embed_970f26f621cfa3ae3eec7e2a6b0e8c97" src="//codepen.io/css-tricks/embed/970f26f621cfa3ae3eec7e2a6b0e8c97?height=675&amp;theme-id=1&amp;slug-hash=970f26f621cfa3ae3eec7e2a6b0e8c97&amp;default-tab=result&amp;user=css-tricks" scrolling="no" frameborder="0" height="675" allowtransparency="true" allowfullscreen="true" name="CodePen Embed" title="CodePen Embed" class="cp_embed_iframe " style="width: 100%; overflow: hidden;"></iframe>

    <p class="ex">With this in mind, add the following CSS to the bottom of our <strong>shoestrap.css</strong> file:</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8"><span style="color:#cda869">*</span> {
  -webkit-box-sizing: border-box;
  -moz-box-sizing: border-box;
  box-sizing: border-box;
}
</pre>

    <p>Using the "*" selects all elements. The two additional CSS properties are for other browsers (firefox, safari, etc.).</p>

